Technologies are Tools
Technologies are tools.=C2=A0
I don=E2=80=99t mean that in the normal way that people mean it to say that=
 technology is neither good nor bad.
Tools are good.
Humans can build better things with tools than they can without them.
But tools aren=E2=80=99t the point. They=E2=80=99re tools.
A hammer is useful insofar as it lets people build houses. Houses are the p=
oint, along with everything else that we use tools to build to improve our =
lives.
Back in the day, a single person could and often did build a house with jus=
t a hammer, ax, and saw.
But think of what it took to build the earliest skyscrapers, limited as the=
y were to just ten to twelve stories.=C2=A0
Building a skyscraper took all of the tools required to build a house, and =
many more besides: structural steel, safety elevators, fire-proofing, raft =
foundations, electricity, lightbulbs, plumbing, telephones, and ventilation=
 systems. Each of those had its own history of technological development, a=
nd all came together to make skyscrapers possible.=C2=A0
But those were just the physical things. Building skyscrapers required inve=
stment contracts, bank loans and bonds, lease agreements, insurance, and re=
insurance. Each of these, too, was developed separately over time, and all =
came together to make skyscrapers possible.=C2=A0
You could write a book on every technology that made skyscrapers possible, =
and fill a library with books on every technology that made those technolog=
ies possible. Think of all it takes to make one pencil [ https://substack.c=
om/redirect/1045a38c-106b-4635-b160-20350928ce2f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8=
J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].=C2=A0
But I think you get the point: technologies are cumulative.=C2=A0
The skyscraper is just one example of a much broader pattern. Across every =
domain, from transportation to finance to energy to healthcare, new tools m=
ake better solutions possible.=C2=A0
As technologists develop and improve new technologies, they contribute them=
 to a global toolkit that entrepreneurs can pull from to tackle ever-grande=
r challenges.
The more and better tools, the bigger and harder challenges builders can ad=
dress with them.=C2=A0
People are smart. We=E2=80=99ve solved most of the challenges that are poss=
ible to solve given the tools currently at our disposal, give or take a lit=
tle given the fact that we=E2=80=99re also good at getting in our own way. =
So we build new tools to tackle new challenges.=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s why investors like to ask, =E2=80=9CWhy now?=E2=80=9D What n=
ew technology (or regulation or societal shift, but mainly technology) make=
s it possible for you to solve this now better than anyone else in all of h=
uman history has been able to?=C2=A0
New tools let builders address new challenges, or old challenges in new way=
s.=C2=A0
I think about it like this. We know most of the challenges facing humanity =
and the opportunities that would make an impact, financial and social, if t=
hey were possible to build.=C2=A0
Everyone would use a safe teleportation device if someone figured out how t=
o make one, just as customers would line up for a pill that extended their =
healthspan by decades.=C2=A0
Those ideas are out there, out of reach, waiting for new technologies to fo=
rm a ladder that we can climb to grab them.
But that drawing isn=E2=80=99t quite right. The ladder is more exponential =
[ https://substack.com/redirect/67ba03a9-ab04-4434-b913-ac6d82a25f73?j=3Dey=
J1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] than that. T=
he more tools we have, the faster we can build new tools, and on and on.=C2=
=A0
Everyone understands that bits have been riding Moore=E2=80=99s Law for dec=
ades, but what=E2=80=99s less appreciated is just how many similar curves t=
here are.=C2=A0
Solar and batteries are getting much cheaper. The cost to sequence the huma=
n genome is falling precipitously. SpaceX is driving down the cost of launc=
hing things to space. Capacitors are on their own Moore=E2=80=99s Law-like =
trend. Blockspace has dropped from dollars to less than a penny per transac=
tion. The price of intelligence got cut in half just last week.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s an embarrassment of riches, made more legible by software. As =
Michael Mauboussin said on  [ https://substack.com/redirect/9720a19a-11e4-4=
6f5-9928-5fcd0c4b4d3d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOs=
a8-6m8ExkRNpU ]Invest Like the Best [ https://substack.com/redirect/9720a19=
a-11e4-46f5-9928-5fcd0c4b4d3d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlX=
XepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]:=C2=A0
Whatever problems face us, we have more tools in the toolbox, more building=
 blocks to solve it. And because we have digital technologies, it allows us=
 to search the space much faster than we could before. And hence, we can co=
me up with solutions faster than we could before.=C2=A0
Which is all a long way of saying: however bullish you are on technology co=
mpanies, you=E2=80=99re not bullish enough.
There have never been more powerful tools available than there are today, w=
hich means that the challenges entrepreneurs can solve, the incumbents they=
 can attack, and the businesses they can build will be bigger than they eve=
r have been.=C2=A0
It sounds simple when you say it. It=E2=80=99s left curve.=C2=A0
But my bet is that it=E2=80=99s also true. Different problems require diffe=
rent tools.=C2=A0
The Right Tools for the Job
There=E2=80=99s a weird thing that happens in tech where people pit differe=
nt categories of technology against each other. =E2=80=9CIf you=E2=80=99re =
in crypto, pivot to AI [ https://substack.com/redirect/ea93fbf4-4d7e-49f8-8=
f65-fd2938e63f9d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m=
8ExkRNpU ],=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9CDon=E2=80=99t waste your time on SaaS when=
 you could build deep tech.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s a zero sum way of thinking about an inherently positive sum =
process. It lacks nuance, because it starts from the tools as opposed to th=
e problems the tools are needed to solve.=C2=A0=C2=A0
The right set of tools for the problem depends on the type of problem being=
 solved.
Certain problems are best solved with software, and others are best solved =
with hardware.
Some industries are information industries.=C2=A0
Most of the value created in tech over the past half-century has come from =
applying software tools to information industry challenges. Microsoft broug=
ht work onto the computer. Facebook connected people across the globe. Goog=
le organized the world=E2=80=99s information. Apple did this=E2=80=A6=C2=A0
Software offered radically better tools to handle information than anything=
 that came before it, which meant there has been a ton of opportunity in cr=
ushing previously manual things into apps, as it were.=C2=A0
Traditional software continues to improve, and entrepreneurs can do more wi=
th software now than they could before, but recent improvements have been m=
uch more marginal than the jump from no software to software, from on-prem =
to cloud, or from desktop to mobile. Most of the really big challenges that=
 can be addressed with traditional software, have been.=C2=A0
Obviously, there are still some really big information challenges left to b=
e solved, they just require more powerful software tools than SaaS. This is=
 why investors are excited about crypto and AI. They can solve problems in =
the world=E2=80=99s two largest information industries - finance and knowle=
dge work.=C2=A0
Take finance. Money, at this point, is information. It primarily exists as =
entries in databases. It is a software problem.=C2=A0=C2=A0
One of the biggest innovations in fintech has been getting rid of physical =
bank branches. Crypto=E2=80=99s innovation is getting rid of the banks alto=
gether. Once the rough edges are smoothed out, getting rid of middlemen mea=
ns structurally superior unit economics.
For example, Stripe recently announced [ https://substack.com/redirect/f65b=
916c-ee53-4421-9f75-a20ae23a5fec?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZj=
mlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] that it=E2=80=99s accepting payments in stableco=
ins, and no wonder: it will pay sub-penny fees instead of the 3% it pays to=
 Visa currently, improving its margins while speeding up settlement times. =
Fundamentally better, faster, and cheaper.=C2=A0
Knowledge work, too, is an information industry, and a massive one that has=
n=E2=80=99t really been directly addressable by tech companies. With AI, it=
 is, and very big businesses are being built that offer intelligence on-dem=
and.=C2=A0
Crypto and AI are alpha-tools in information industries. They offer the bes=
t possible set of tools to fix the problems they were designed to fix. They=
=E2=80=99re disruptive innovations vis a vis finance and knowledge work.=C2=
=A0
They are sufficient. It=E2=80=99s hard to imagine a scenario in which build=
ing hardware fixes the current bottlenecks in finance or knowledge work. It=
 would only add unnecessary cost and complexity.=C2=A0
Information industries will not be won with hardware. They will be won with=
 software. And as new solutions create new challenges =E2=80=93 see: Wiz [ =
https://substack.com/redirect/f2d31a13-adfb-44d1-83b2-eaf5f4dafb00?j=3DeyJ1=
IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] solving securi=
ty challenges presented by the cloud =E2=80=93=C2=A0 there will always be n=
ew challenges to solve with radically better software tools.
Other industries, though, are matter industries.
Think energy or agriculture. These things are necessarily physical. Electri=
city requires electrons. Digital food doesn=E2=80=99t fill bellies.
For the past few decades, as software has eaten the world, entrepreneurs an=
d incumbents alike have attempted to fix these industries with software. Th=
ey=E2=80=99ve made them more efficient, perhaps, but they=E2=80=99ve only n=
ibbled around the edges. Giving a power plant a CRM only does so much.
The fact is, physical challenges require physical solutions, and humans hav=
e spent millennia developing physical solutions.=C2=A0
Matter industry incumbents got where they are by using tools that were newl=
y available at the time of their formation to solve old challenges in new w=
ays. They were once Techno-Industrials.=C2=A0
Boeing is a dominant airplane manufacturer today because its 707 used a jet=
 engine to cut travel times in half way back in 1958.=C2=A0
Exxon Mobil (the result of a merger between Standard Oil of New Jersey and =
Standard Oil of New York) is still the largest American energy company toda=
y because Standard vertically integrated around innovations in refining tec=
hniques, pipeline networks, storage and distribution, and more way back in =
the late 19th century.=C2=A0
You can=E2=80=99t build a larger airline manufacturer than Boeing or a larg=
er energy company than Exxon Mobil with software alone or by making slightl=
y better jet engines or oil refineries.=C2=A0
Century-old incumbents have remained comfortably atop these industries beca=
use attempts to innovate with software have been sustaining innovations. In=
cumbents have adopted the good ones to improve their bottom lines, but soft=
ware alone hasn=E2=80=99t reshaped these industries.=C2=A0
You need to introduce an entirely new paradigm, which requires reaching muc=
h higher on the cumulative technology ladder than previous solutions. Becau=
se while the accumulation of tools is continuous, there are discrete period=
s in history when those tools have gotten better enough to make new solutio=
ns possible.=C2=A0
I think we=E2=80=99re in one of those periods.=C2=A0
Instead of designing slightly better versions of old products =E2=80=93 not=
 better enough to displace incumbents =E2=80=93 or fixing inefficiencies wi=
th software, entrepreneurs are designing radically better vertically integr=
ated systems from the ground up with cutting edge hardware and software.=C2=
=A0
They=E2=80=99re mixing and matching whatever tools are needed to get the jo=
b done: SaaS, AI, AR, mobile, crypto, biotech, and all of the million thing=
s that go into what people call =E2=80=9Cdeep tech.=E2=80=9D
What is Deep Tech?=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CDeep tech=E2=80=9D is a nebulous term that=E2=80=99s used to mean =
doing something with the most advanced technology at our disposal, particul=
arly if that technology touches the physical world. It=E2=80=99s confused w=
ith hard tech and frontier tech, because, well, it=E2=80=99s confusing.=C2=
=A0
Part of the confusion around the term comes from the fact that two categori=
es of companies get lumped into deep tech: Toolmakers and Techno-Industrial=
s.
Toolmakers operate at the very bleeding edge, coming up with brand new scie=
nce and technology, with a primary focus on the science and technology them=
selves.=C2=A0
Techno-Industrials start with the challenge they want to solve, and use eve=
ry tool at their disposal, including some at the cutting edge and even some=
 that they have to create themselves, to solve that challenge.=C2=A0
When I first wrote about them [ https://substack.com/redirect/1742c303-3dbc=
-4d55-9b7c-91e7f2dfa277?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbq=
Osa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], I defined Techno-Industrials as companies that =E2=80=9C=
use technology to build atoms-based products with structurally superior uni=
t economics with the ultimate goal of winning on cost in large existing mar=
kets, or expanding or creating new markets where there is pent-up demand.=
=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Both Toolmakers and Techno-Industrials are important, but they=E2=80=99re d=
ifferent.
Toolmakers are closer to what I=E2=80=99d categorize as actual deep tech. T=
hey are solving deeply technical problems in order to give humanity fundame=
ntally new capabilities. They=E2=80=99re often the ones pushing the exponen=
tial curves. A company developing a new type of semiconductor, new material=
s, or more efficient solar cells might fit into this category.
Techno-Industrials, on the other hand, are the ones riding exponential curv=
es. They=E2=80=99re integrators as much as they are innovators, incorporati=
ng a number of technologies that hit just the right spot on their curves to=
 be practically and economically useful in solving a particular challenge (=
new or old) in a better way.=C2=A0
