ferent approach.=C2=A0
Advances in AI and software more broadly meant that it was possible to buil=
d Lattice, an operating system that connects all of Anduril=E2=80=99s hardw=
are. SpaceX showed that it was possible to manufacture hardware and sell it=
 to the government more cheaply than incumbents could. Together, they prese=
nted the opportunity to build a defense company with better margins.=C2=A0
Over the past seven years, Anduril both proved that it was possible to buil=
d a big business in defense and educated the market on how the defense indu=
stry works. If you ask a random VC what =E2=80=9Ccost-plus=E2=80=9D means t=
oday, most will actually know what you=E2=80=99re talking about!=C2=A0
As Anduril co-founder Trae Stephens wrote in Venture Capital=E2=80=99s Spac=
e for Sheep [ https://substack.com/redirect/2f351271-0a47-4ed1-9423-6245cda=
9ec0b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]:
Today, Anduril is valued at more than $10 billion, and the hype has followe=
d. In 2014, just $200 million in venture investment flowed into defense tec=
hnology; last year, that figure topped $6 billion [ https://substack.com/re=
direct/aff8e78b-01cd-4065-8a54-a941aa6467e7?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7G=
nA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. Investors see our success as proof t=
he defense industry can generate serious returns, and now they=E2=80=99re h=
oping to get a piece of the next Anduril.
That, Trae believes, is the wrong lesson to take from Anduril. =E2=80=9CIn =
all likelihood,=E2=80=9D he writes, =E2=80=9Canother defense tech company o=
perating at Anduril=E2=80=99s scale won=E2=80=99t come out of this hype cyc=
le.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=C2=A0
The right lesson to take from Anduril is that it=E2=80=99s possible to buil=
d very big businesses by applying a suite of cutting edge tools and process=
es to the right bottlenecks in large, seemingly impenetrable industries.=C2=
=A0
And thanks to the power law, there will be one really big winner in each in=
dustry:
Defense, like all technology sectors, is ruled by the power law: a single, =
prime mover will claim the vast majority of profits even after the sector h=
as reached maturity. The company that carves out a new investment category =
usually stays on top.
In other words, catching the power law winners requires looking in new sect=
ors.
Uber, he points out, has a market cap three times as large as the next ten =
ride-sharing companies combined.=C2=A0
The same dynamic plays out across categories:=C2=A0
At $47 billion, Coinbase=E2=80=99s market cap is more than double the next =
ten crypto companies combined. At $180 billion, SpaceX=E2=80=99s market cap=
 exceeds that of the next twenty space companies combined. And at $1.2 tril=
lion, Meta=E2=80=99s market cap is more than double the next dozen social m=
edia companies combined.
In each of these examples, the power law winner used the best tools at its =
disposal to solve a particular problem.=C2=A0
Uber took advantage of GPS and payments on phones and mutual ratings system=
s, plus post-Global Financial Crisis unemployment, to make transportation m=
ore reliable.=C2=A0
Coinbase used modern consumer software, custody, payments, and ID verificat=
ion to make Bitcoin accessible to normal buyers.=C2=A0
SpaceX used cutting edge rocket technology, materials, and manufacturing pr=
ocesses to make rockets reusable and lower the cost of launch.=C2=A0
Meta used .edu email addresses, digital photography, Ajax, online advertisi=
ng, and eventually mobile to connect people with their friends online, unde=
r their real names.
What=E2=80=99s so compelling about Anduril is that while Uber, Coinbase, Sp=
aceX, and Meta took on fairly weak competitors, Anduril is going after five=
 dominant incumbents worth more than half a trillion dollars combined and s=
tarting to win.
And it makes sense!=C2=A0
The tools at their disposal are more powerful than ever. We=E2=80=99re hitt=
ing the right point on the cumulative technology ladder to go after powerfu=
l incumbents in large physical industries to tackle the biggest challenges =
facing humanity.=C2=A0
The next Anduril won=E2=80=99t be in defense. There will be many, one in ea=
ch large matter industry dominated by creaky incumbents (and many in inform=
ation industries as well, although we=E2=80=99ll save that for another piec=
e). They will have a shot at building $100 billion+ businesses, like Meta, =
Uber, and SpaceX have, and like Coinbase and Anduril may soon. And most of =
them have been started or will be started in the next few years.=C2=A0
Why Now?=C2=A0
There are a few big reasons that I think now is such a fertile time to buil=
d $100 billion+ Techno-Industrials:
Tools. There are simply more tools at builders=E2=80=99 disposal =E2=80=93 =
AI, traditional software, improving hardware, programmable biology, cheaper=
