nA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); t=
ext-decoration: underline;">Stripe recently announced</a><span> that it&#82=
17;s accepting payments in stablecoins, and no wonder: it will pay sub-penn=
y fees instead of the 3% it pays to Visa currently, improving its margins w=
hile speeding up settlement times. Fundamentally better, faster, and cheape=
r.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; lin=
e-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Knowledge work, too, is an information=
 industry, and a massive one that hasn&#8217;t really been directly address=
able by tech companies. With AI, it is, and very big businesses are being b=
uilt that offer intelligence on-demand.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54,=
 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Cr=
ypto and AI are alpha-tools in information industries. They offer the best =
possible set of tools to fix the problems they were designed to fix. They&#=
8217;re </span><strong>disruptive innovations</strong><span> vis a vis fina=
nce and knowledge work.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55);=
 font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">They are sufficie=
nt. It&#8217;s hard to imagine a scenario in which building hardware fixes =
the current bottlenecks in finance or knowledge work. It would only add unn=
ecessary cost and complexity.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); =
font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Information =
industries will not be won with hardware. They will be won with software. A=
nd as new solutions create new challenges &#8211; see: </span><a href=3D"ht=
